<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Site and thier Impotents in your games<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(2.67)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10500'>Charles "Kakita" Bickford</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10500&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 23, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> One of the more interesting aspects of Decipher&#8217;s Lord of the Rings is that you&#8217;re never quite sure where you&#8217;re going until you get there. As your fellowship moves along the Adventure Path -- particularly if you&#8217;re going first -- often you have no clue what the next site will be; what it&#8217;s game text is, how many twilight tokens you&#8217;ll have to add for moving there, or even whether or not it will have any traits you want or don&#8217;t want (underground, river, etc.). <br>
<br>
It doesn&#8217;t have to be this way, however. There are cards that allow you to manipulate the site path both when you&#8217;re a Shadow player or a Fellowship player. Furthermore, how you intend to play your deck should have a huge impact on what sites you choose to include in it. It&#8217;s a subtle, but often important part of deck construction. <br>
<br>
SITE SELECTION <br>
<br>
The first thing you should do, before you choose sites, is build your deck. Remember, no matter how many &#8220;site control&#8221; cards you include, they may not come up in your hand, so you must build your deck to stand alone and then add sites that compliment it. Never do this in the reverse order (i.e. build your deck to match your sites). If you do, you&#8217;ll be doing yourself a great disservice. <br>
<br>
The next thing you must do is ask yourself how badly your deck needs to go first. This should be the largest factor to consider when looking at your site selection. If you choose to go second, often you will want your sites to aid your Shadow strategy. Nazgûl players have quickly learned that it is best to go second and make your opponent move to their site 2 (often Bree Streets or Weatherhills) and their site 3 (typically Ford of Bruinen). <br>
<br>
If you choose to make an effort to bid high enough to go first, however, you have a whole other list of things to consider. Remember, if you go first, odds are you&#39;ll be moving to whatever sites your opponent puts out over the course of the game. If they&#39;re as sharp as you, they&#39;ve tailored their Adventure Deck to have a few sites that can help their Shadow package against Fellowship strategies they&#39;re particularly weak against. If you&#39;re playing one of those Fellowship strategies, you might find yourself in a bit of trouble &quot;down the road&quot;; that is to say, later in the game as you move down the Adventure Path. <br>
<br>
SITE CONTROL <br>
<br>
Once you have decided that your site 1 is critical to your deck and chose to go first, you have to decide how important the rest of the site path is to your deck. Take a look at the list of available sites and decide if there are one or two sites that can really kill your deck strategy. If there are, it&#39;s time to start thinking about how much site control your deck needs. <br>
<br>
When I say &quot;site control&quot;, I&#39;m talking about the ability to change what sites make up the Adventure Path. Currently, there are only 3 cards that allow you to do this in LotR: Pathfinder, a Gondor event; Thrór&#39;s Map, a Shire possession; and Úlairë Nelya, a Nazgûl minion. Since Nelya&#39;s text only applies once your opponent has put a site out, he really doesn&#39;t help your Fellowship much. So we&#8217;ll focus on Pathfinder and Thrór&#39;s Map. <br>
<br>
Pathfinder <br>
Gondor Event, Cost: 0 <br>
&#8220;Fellowship or Regroup: Spot a ranger to play the fellowship&#8217;s next site (replacing opponent&#8217;s site if necessary).&#8221; <br>
<br>
While this is a very useful card, it has several immediate drawbacks. First, it&#8217;s a one time shot. You play the event, it has it&#8217;s effect, and then it goes away. Second, is it&#8217;s not always that useful. If you draw this card right before you&#8217;re supposed to move to the Bridge of Khazad-dûm, it&#8217;s just taking up space. It doesn&#8217;t matter if your Bridge or your opponent&#8217;s comes out. You could still play it to get it out of your hand, but it really gains you nothing. <br>
<br>
Third, you have to spot a ranger to play it. While this is probably not too difficult, as three of the most often seen companions -- Arwen, Boromir, and Aragorn -- are rangers, they are not always included in every deck. So if you&#8217;re playing a Gandalf deck with Gimli and Legolas, for example, this card is off-limits to you. <br>
<br>
Nevertheless, if you are one of the many players with rangers in their decks who don&#8217;t want to move to Brown Lands or Anduin Confluence, then a couple of Pathfinders may be a worthy addition to your deck. Or you might go with... <br>
<br>
Thrór&#39;s Map <br>
Shire Possession, Cost: 0 <br>
&#8220;Plays to your support area. Fellowship or Regroup: Exert a hobbit to play the fellowship&#8217;s next site (replacing opponent&#8217;s site if necessary).&#8221; <br>
<br>
If you&#8217;re concerned about site control in your deck, then this is a surefire way to go. It comes out for free and stays out, so you always have the option of using it. That&#8217;s because if you can&#8217;t use it&#8217;s game text, you&#8217;ve lost, as only hobbits can carry the Ring (Frodo or Sam). Thrór&#39;s Map is just one of the best cards in the game. It can go in any deck that feels it needs it and is always there when you want to use it. <br>
<br>
Sites and the Adventure Path are of critical importance to any deck you play. You can have control over where your fellowship moves if you choose to, it&#8217;s all a matter of how important it is to you and your deck strategy&#8230; or how much you want to mess up your opponent&#8217;s strategy of going second by getting your sites out anyway. <br>
